re it has been established since medieval times in the counties of Tipperary and Kilkenny."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mabel Stapleton was born in 1195, in Stapleton on Tees, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Geoffrey of Stapleton. She married William Scot de Calverley. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. She died in Calverley, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1195–":"1195–Surnud","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1193–Male":"1193–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1210–1261":"1210–1261","1238–1317":"1238–1317","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1246–1274":"1246–1274","1249–Female":"1249–Surnud","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1255–1308":"1255–1308","1150–1204":"1150–1204","1252":"1252","1274":"1274","abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","abt 1252":"umbes 1252","1261":"1261","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1238":"1238","1249":"1249","1204":"1204","abt 1249":"umbes 1249","1246":"1246","1179":"1179","1255":"1255","1210":"1210","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Stapleton on Tees, Yorkshire, England":"Stapleton on Tees, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calverley, West Yorkshire, England.":"Calverley, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1195–":"1195–Kuoll